biography: Jonathan Dickinson 1688-1747, was an American Presbyterian clergyman, and a founder and first president of the College of New Jersey, now Princeton University. Born in Massachusetts, Dickinson graduated from Yale in 1706. He joined the newly founded Presbyterian body in the Middle Colonies in 1717 and became a leader in theological thought and debate. In 1746, he obtained a charter for the College of New Jersey. In 1747 he opened the institution at his house in Elizabethtown (now Elizabeth), New Jersey, and served as the College’s first President for a brief period before his death.
